== Bodycentered practice
#v(15pt)

Rhythmic precision is not primarily a cognitive achievement — it is a physical one. Before a rhythm can be internalized as sound, it must be embodied as movement: the contraction and release of muscles, the alternation of limbs, the coordination of gesture and timing. This chapter examines the implications of that fundamental fact for rhythmic practice. We argue that effective rhythm training, particularly when working with unfamiliar subdivision feels, requires a deliberate shift of attention away from auditory expectation and toward physical sensation. Practicing in this way exposes a characteristic perceptual challenge — what we call the banana skin effect — that arises when a familiar rhythmic result is produced through an unfamiliar movement pattern. We describe practical strategies for navigating this challenge, including the counterintuitive technique of practicing with ears closed, and conclude with a broader reflection on the idea of performing as a form of dance: an approach in which sound becomes the natural byproduct of embodied, coordinated movement rather than its primary goal.

=== Muscles

Muscles operate in a binary manner: they either contract or release. This
fundamental principle suggests that rhythm practice should initially be broken
down into binary movement patterns, focusing on essential oppositions such as
left/right, up/down, or in/out.

To develop rhythmic precision and control, it is crucial to isolate the physical
movements required to produce sound on the instrument. Practicing these movements
separately at first ensures that rhythm and feel are internalized independently
from melodic patterns, preventing the mere memorization of fixed sequences.

This approach is especially valuable when learning unconventional rhythmic feels,
as it helps break habitual pre-auditory and movement reflexes. By grounding
practice in pure physical and rhythmic awareness, musicians build a foundation
for greater rhythmic accuracy, flexibility, and expressive depth.

=== Banana Skin

When practicing swung subdivisions with a focus on movement and muscular action,
as outlined above, an algorithmic process unfolds, generating unexpected or
non-pre-audiated results. This occurs because the body's motion dictates the
rhythmic outcome rather than pre-heard musical expectations.

Furthermore, performers often encounter familiar rhythmic results — but produced
through an unfamiliar movement pattern. This mismatch between expected sound and
unexpected motion creates a perceptual contradiction, disrupting focus and
timekeeping.

I refer to this phenomenon as the "banana skin effect" — a momentary slip in
rhythmic awareness caused by the dissonance between habitual pre-auditory
expectations and newly acquired movement patterns.

=== Ears Closed

To avoid this banana skin effect, I suggest that students practice the exercise
with their ears closed. While it might seem counterintuitive — almost nonsensical
— to ask a musician to play without listening, the goal is to shift the focus
entirely to movement and muscular action.

By temporarily disengaging auditory feedback, the performer is compelled to rely
solely on physical sensation and coordination, reinforcing rhythmic accuracy from
a kinesthetic foundation. Gradually, listening can be reintroduced — but as if
the sound were external, detached from one's own playing. This method helps
bridge the gap between unexpected motion and expected rhythm, strengthening
control and deepening rhythmic perception beyond habitual reflexes.

=== Dancing on the Instrument

Performing on an instrument is a complex interplay of movements, most of which
are highly refined and precise. This process can be experienced as a dance,
engaging the entire body in a coordinated flow of motion and muscular activity.

When a performer shifts their focus to the physical experience of dancing on the
instrument, the sonic result becomes a side effect — a natural consequence of
embodied movement rather than the primary goal. This approach fosters a deeper
connection to rhythm and feel, freeing the performer from over-intellectualizing
sound production and allowing music to emerge organically from motion.

== Mechanical Sub-Harmonics

In the pitch domain, the first sub-harmonic of a tone (the tone to which our
tone is the first harmonic) is one octave below, which means half the frequency.
In the rhythm domain this would translate to half the speed:

 #figure(
  image("Figures/subharmonics-a.png"),
)

When we consider straight subdivisions, halving the speed is equivalent to
selecting every second accent. So in the rhythm domain, sub-harmonics of a
subdivision rate can be obtained by grouping those subdivisions: two-grouping
equals the first sub-harmonic, three-grouping the second, and so forth:

 #figure(
  image("Figures/subharmonics-b.png")
)

We call this the *mechanical sub-harmonic*.

When applied to swinging subdivisions, mechanical sub-harmonics render a rhythm
that is at first not foreseen, or pre-heard, with the potential of a _banana
skin_ effect for the performer:

 #figure(
  image("Figures/subharmonics-c.png")
)

=== Pattern vs Swing

Each element of the collection can be considered either as a specific swing of
$n$ subdivisions (the _tuplet-size_) or as a pattern consisting of $n$ accents
within a duration of $d$ (_absolute size_).

Hereunder an exercise where I use two patterns (a) and (b), both as pattern and
swing. 

